My Project

Canopy architecture in wheat affects light penetration & subsequent leaf photosynthesis which in turn influences solar radiation use efficiency during stem elongation and anthesis, ultimately affecting above ground biomass & crop yield. The aim of this study is to investigate if two contrasting leaf architecture influence key economic traits of spring wheat.In this experiment important traits are evaluated for canopy architecture in a study population (n=315 lines) in two replications. Those lines included both erect and floppy canopy types, were grown in 2019 wheat season in Ginninderra Experiment Station, ACT. The traits evaluated were top leaf erectness score during anthesis, anthesis biomass, days to anthesis, plant height, peduncle length and grain yield. Data collected of those triats were then cleaned & analysed in R using tidyverse and kableExtra packages.

Preliminary results

In this study we evaluated canopy architecture lines developed from Australian commercial spring wheats. Line selection based on canopy architecture looks promising at the plot scale providing weather conditions are favourable leading up to flowering time so that the genetic potential of the upper leaves in the canopy is properly expressed. As is evident in Figure 1 and Figure 2 imporant economic traits yield and anthesis biomass respond positively to lower canopy score (erect leaf types), which corroborates previous findings by R.A Richars et al. 2019. However,because of drier growing season of 2019 in ACT leading up to flowering, the architecture score was skewed to more errect types such as lower score values in 1 to 10 scale(Table 1). Another imporatnt phenological trait of days to flowering has shown that more spread on floppy end than that of erect end as in Figure 3. Plant height and peduncle length demonstrate linear relationship as show in Figure 4. This study is expected to help easily observed traits that could be important in breeding so as to increase canopy light interception and radiation use efficiency during the critical period of yield formation and thereby grain yield, canopy photosynthesis and crop biomass.

Plots from R

ges_2019 %>% 
  filter(canopy_score<= 3.0,plot_yield>=mean(plot_yield)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = canopy_score, y = plot_yield,color =as.factor(rep), size = anthesis_biomass)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_colour_manual(values = c("red", "blue"))

Figure 1: Grain yield & anthesis biomass in errect type spring wheat lines 

ges_2019 %>% 
  filter(canopy_score> 3.0,plot_yield<mean(plot_yield)) %>%
